From: rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller)
Subject: TAMU is kind of nice, but it has some difficulties.
Date: 28 Sep 1993 11:44:35 GMT

Joe.Klemmer@f370.n109.z1.fidonet.org (Joe Klemmer) writes:
>Is anyone using the TAMU release?  It really looks good and I'd just like
>to get some feedback on it if someone's using it.

I picked up the latest release (TAMU.99pl12+) just to try it out...

I finally got color X to work on one of my Compaqs, though it didn't use
the left 2 inches of the screen... <sigh>

It gave me a chance to try out the X File Manager ("xfm"), which I never
would have bothered with otherwise.  It's pretty nice!  Its almost Mac-like
simplicity that "xfm" presents just may be the key to weaning my wife away
from MS-DOS (and thus recovering another 20 MB of disk space!!).

There were problems though.  I had to symbolically link all the shared
X libraries up into the root directory (because LD_LIBRARY_PATH wasn't
being searched properly), and I had to "unset TERMCAP" and "stty sane"
to get xterms to behave properly when logging in through xdm.

The main thing that irks me though is that even without Emacs I'm almost
filling my disk!  Maybe it's all the X stuff, but JEEZ!  I used to have
about 12 MEGAbytes more free space when I used the SLS base distribution
and TinyX.  With *that*, I had GhostScript too!  I just don't know what
could be taking up all that space in the TAMU distribution...

Another thing that bugged me was that I couldn't get publicly available
binaries (for X) to run under TAMU... maybe they would run, now that I
have the X libraries linked into the root directory.  Really strange.

Yes, I'm aware that SLS has problems.  But I think it's better than the
TAMU distribution for a few reasons:  SLS packs a lot of functionality
into a little disk space.  SLS lets you CHOOSE what to install and what
not to install.  And of some not-so-minor importance:  SLS *works*.

