From: drs0587@net.tamu.edu (Dave Safford)
Subject: Re: TAMU is kind of nice, but it has some diffi
Date: 28 Sep 1993 13:47:50 GMT
Reply-To: drs0587@net.tamu.edu

In article 289833INNd86@uwm.edu, rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller) writes:
<Joe.Klemmer@f370.n109.z1.fidonet.org (Joe Klemmer) writes:
<>Is anyone using the TAMU release?  It really looks good and I'd just like
<>to get some feedback on it if someone's using it.
<
<I picked up the latest release (TAMU.99pl12+) just to try it out...
<
...
<Yes, I'm aware that SLS has problems.  But I think it's better than the
<TAMU distribution for a few reasons:  SLS packs a lot of functionality
<into a little disk space.  SLS lets you CHOOSE what to install and what
<not to install.  And of some not-so-minor importance:  SLS *works*.
<
Just a couple of comments:
1. thanks to a number of helpful testers, all the problems mentioned by rick
   (plus a couple others) are documented in an ERRATA file in the TAMU top 
   level ftp directory, and are easily fixed.  TAMU.99p12 is a whole new
   release created from scratch based on a complete BSD style source tree,
   and suffers the typical minor bugs of such a massive undertaking.  At least
   all the known bugs are documented.  To some sites, such as TAMU, the
   availability of a full source tree is critical to future plans for linux,
   and these needs are not addressed by SLS.
2. TAMU.99p12 does have a working automatic network installation/configuration.
   This may not be of significance to home users, but is important to 
   use of linux on campus.
2. TAMU.99p12 does let you choose whether or not to load X11.  A real
   package system along the lines of Sun's is in the works, which will
   have definite advantages over the SLS disk set method. (Finer granularity,
   package dependencies, ...).  With this package system, you will be able to 
   see exactly where the space is being used, and tailor your configuration
   to your needs.

dave safford


